# The Event Loop

JavaScript runs **one thread**. Concurrency is an illusion built from a loop: run a task to completion → drain the microtask queue → maybe render → next task.

## The two queues (know the order cold)

- **Task (macrotask) queue**: `setTimeout`, events, I/O callbacks
- **Microtask queue**: promise callbacks (`.then`, `await` continuations), `queueMicrotask` — drained **completely after every task, before rendering**

```javascript
console.log('1');
setTimeout(() => console.log('2'), 0);
Promise.resolve().then(() => console.log('3'));
console.log('4');
// → 1, 4, 3, 2   (sync first, then ALL microtasks, then the next task)
```

## Why it matters in real apps

- **Blocking**: a 200ms synchronous loop freezes clicks, scrolling, rendering — everything. There is no 'background' unless you create it (Web Workers) or yield (`await`, `setTimeout` chunking)
- **Starvation**: microtasks that queue more microtasks (a promise loop) block rendering *forever* — tasks at least let the browser render between them
- **`async/await` is sugar**: everything after `await` is a microtask continuation. `await` doesn't 'pause the thread' — it schedules the rest and returns
- Angular's zone.js (next lessons) literally patches these APIs to know when to check for changes

## Chunking long work

```javascript
async function processBigList(items) {
    for (let i = 0; i < items.length; i++) {
        process(items[i]);
        if (i % 500 === 0) await new Promise(r => setTimeout(r));  // yield a task → browser renders
    }
}
// Truly heavy work → Web Worker: a separate thread with message passing
```

DevTools Performance tab: long yellow blocks = tasks over 50ms = jank you can see in this model.

# The Angular Memory Leak

The mechanism (closures lesson + observables lesson combined): a component subscribes to a stream that **outlives it** (store, interval, router events, WebSocket, global service Subject). Component destroyed → subscription still registered → callback's closure keeps the whole component (and its injected services, its data) reachable. Navigate back and forth 50 times = 50 zombie components running their callbacks.

```typescript
ngOnInit() {
    this.store.cart$.subscribe(c => this.cart = c);          // leak: store outlives component
    interval(1000).subscribe(() => this.tick());              // leak: never completes
    this.http.get('/api/x').subscribe(d => this.data = d);    // NOT a leak: completes after one emit
}
```

The HttpClient exception explains the confusion: completion tears subscriptions down, so one-shot HTTP 'forgotten' subscribes are messy but not leaky. Infinite streams are the ones that bite.

## The modern kill-switch: takeUntilDestroyed

```typescript
export class CartBadgeComponent {
    private store = inject(CartStore);
    count = 0;
    constructor() {
        this.store.cart$.pipe(
            map(c => c.items.length),
            takeUntilDestroyed()                 // auto-unsubscribes on component destroy
        ).subscribe(n => this.count = n);
    }
}
```

Injection-context based (constructor/field initializers); elsewhere pass `takeUntilDestroyed(this.destroyRef)`. This replaced the old `private destroy$ = new Subject()` + `ngOnDestroy` boilerplate.

## Better: don't subscribe manually at all

Preference ladder:
1. **`toSignal(obs$)`** or **`async` pipe** — Angular owns the subscription lifecycle entirely; plus OnPush integration for free
2. `takeUntilDestroyed` when you truly need imperative subscription (side effects on emission)
3. Manual `Subscription` + `ngOnDestroy` — legacy code only

Most manual subscriptions exist to copy stream values onto component fields for the template — which is exactly what `toSignal`/`async` do declaratively:

```typescript
readonly count = toSignal(this.store.cart$.pipe(map(c => c.items.length)), { initialValue: 0 });
```

## Finding leaks

DevTools → Memory → heap snapshot → navigate away/back 5× → snapshot → compare: detached component instances accumulating = leak. Filter by your component class name.

# Angular DI — Same Principle, Different Container

Your DIP lesson applies verbatim; Angular's container has its own mechanics worth mastering.

## Providing

```typescript
@Injectable({ providedIn: 'root' })      // app singleton, TREE-SHAKABLE — the default choice
export class OrderService { }

// inject() — the modern access pattern (constructor params still fine)
export class OrderListComponent {
    private orders = inject(OrderService);
    private config = inject(APP_CONFIG);
}
```

`providedIn: 'root'` beats NgModule/`providers: []` registration because unused services get tree-shaken out of the bundle.

## The injector tree — scoping like your ASP.NET lifetimes

Resolution walks **up**: component's injector → parent components → route (lazy boundaries create injectors) → root. Provide at a component to get **one instance per component subtree**:

```typescript
@Component({ providers: [WizardStateService] })   // each wizard instance gets its OWN state
export class CheckoutWizardComponent { }
```

That's Angular's 'scoped lifetime' — scope = component subtree instead of HTTP request. Sibling wizards don't share state; destroy the component, the service goes too (its `DestroyRef` fires — pairs with the leak lesson).

| ASP.NET Core | Angular analog |
|---|---|
| Singleton | providedIn: 'root' |
| Scoped (per request) | component/route `providers` (per subtree) |
| Named/keyed services | InjectionToken |

## InjectionToken — DI for non-classes

```typescript
export const API_URL = new InjectionToken<string>('API_URL');
providers: [{ provide: API_URL, useValue: environment.apiUrl }]

// and the OCP trick you know from C# — multi providers = IEnumerable<T>:
providers: [
    { provide: VALIDATOR, useClass: EmailValidator, multi: true },
    { provide: VALIDATOR, useClass: PhoneValidator, multi: true },
]
const validators = inject(VALIDATOR);   // array of all — strategies, Angular edition
```

`useClass` (swap implementation), `useFactory` (construction logic + deps), `useExisting` (alias). Testing = providing fakes: `TestBed.configureTestingModule({ providers: [{ provide: OrderService, useValue: fake }] })` — the whole testability payoff of DIP.

Gotcha worth knowing: providing the same service at multiple tree levels **shadows** — a component asking for it gets the nearest, which may not be the singleton your service assumed (two 'singletons' with diverging state = confusing bugs). Provide at root unless subtree scoping is the *point*.

# Reactive Forms

Template-driven forms are fine for a login box. Business forms — dynamic rows, cross-field rules, server validation — want the reactive API: the form model lives in **code** (testable, composable), the template just binds.

## Typed forms (14+) — use the inference

```typescript
private fb = inject(NonNullableFormBuilder);   // avoids string|null everywhere

form = this.fb.group({
    customer: this.fb.control('', [Validators.required, Validators.minLength(3)]),
    email: this.fb.control('', [Validators.required, Validators.email]),
    lines: this.fb.array([this.buildLine()]),
});

buildLine() {
    return this.fb.group({ sku: [''], qty: this.fb.control(1, Validators.min(1)) });
}
addLine() { this.form.controls.lines.push(this.buildLine()); }   // dynamic rows = FormArray
```

`form.value` is now deeply typed; `form.getRawValue()` includes disabled controls (the difference bites on submit).

## Custom + cross-field validators

```typescript
// single control
export function skuExists(api: CatalogApi): AsyncValidatorFn {
    return control => api.checkSku(control.value).pipe(
        map(exists => exists ? null : { skuUnknown: true }),
        catchError(() => of(null)));                     // validation availability ≠ form hostage
}

// cross-field: validator on the GROUP
const dateRange: ValidatorFn = group => {
    const { from, to } = group.value;
    return from && to && from > to ? { dateRange: true } : null;
};
```

Async validators run **after** sync ones pass (no wasted API calls), set `control.pending` — debounce them (`updateOn: 'blur'` or stream-side) to avoid per-keystroke requests (your switchMap lesson applies inside async validators too).

## Server errors belong on controls

```typescript
this.api.save(this.form.getRawValue()).subscribe({
    error: (err: ValidationProblem) => {
        for (const [field, message] of Object.entries(err.errors))
            this.form.get(field)?.setErrors({ server: message });   // ProblemDetails → field errors
    }
});
```

Your ASP.NET ProblemDetails validation response maps naturally onto `setErrors` — one error-display component (`@if (control.errors?.['server'])`) covers both client and server validation uniformly.

## UX contract

Show errors on `touched || submitted`, not while typing the first character; disable submit on `pending`, not just `invalid`; `markAllAsTouched()` on failed submit so every error surfaces. Forms + signals: `form.valueChanges` → `toSignal` for reactive summaries (totals, live previews).

# The HTTP Edge of Your Frontend

## Functional interceptors — Chain of Responsibility, again

```typescript
export const authInterceptor: HttpInterceptorFn = (req, next) => {
    const token = inject(TokenStore).accessToken();
    return next(token ? req.clone({ setHeaders: { Authorization: `Bearer ${token}` } }) : req);
};

export const errorInterceptor: HttpInterceptorFn = (req, next) => {
    const toast = inject(ToastService);
    return next(req).pipe(
        catchError((err: HttpErrorResponse) => {
            if (err.status === 401) inject(Router).navigate(['/login']);
            else if (err.status >= 500) toast.error('Something went wrong');
            return throwError(() => err);          // rethrow — callers may handle specifics
        }));
};

provideHttpClient(withInterceptors([authInterceptor, retryInterceptor, errorInterceptor]))
```

Order matters exactly like ASP.NET middleware (it IS the same pattern — your chain lesson): auth adds headers before retry duplicates the request; error handling wraps everything. Requests are immutable — always `req.clone()`.

## The standard stack (one of each)

1. **Auth** — attach token; on 401, trigger refresh-token flow then **replay the original request** (queue concurrent 401s so ONE refresh happens — a shareReplay'd refresh observable, your multicasting lesson)
2. **Retry** — transient GETs only (`retry({ count: 2, delay: backoff })`); never blind-retry POSTs (idempotency lesson!)
3. **Error normalization** — ProblemDetails → typed AppError; global toasts for 5xx; rethrow for local handling
4. **Loading/correlation** — request counter for a global busy bar; `X-Correlation-Id` header that your ASP.NET logs pick up (observability lesson, connected end-to-end!)

## API layer discipline

Components never call `HttpClient` directly — a service layer per feature returns **typed domain results**:

```typescript
@Injectable({ providedIn: 'root' })
export class OrdersApi {
    private http = inject(HttpClient);
    getOrders(filter: OrderFilter) {
        return this.http.get<OrderDto[]>('/api/orders', { params: toParams(filter) })
            .pipe(map(dtos => dtos.map(toOrder)));    // DTO → domain mapping at the boundary
    }
}
```

The Adapter instinct: backend DTO shapes stop at this layer (rename/reshape here), so an API field rename touches one file, not thirty components. Generate the DTO types from your ASP.NET OpenAPI spec (openapi-typescript / NSwag) — contract drift becomes a compile error instead of a runtime surprise.

# Flexbox

Layout along **one axis** (row or column) with intelligent space distribution. 90% of component-level layout.

## The mental model

Container sets the rules; items negotiate space:

```css
.toolbar {
    display: flex;
    flex-direction: row;        /* main axis (default) */
    justify-content: space-between;  /* MAIN axis distribution */
    align-items: center;             /* CROSS axis alignment */
    gap: 12px;                       /* use gap, not margins between items */
}
```

`justify-*` = main axis; `align-*` = cross axis; `flex-direction` swaps which is which — the eternal confusion, resolved by always asking 'which axis is main right now?'

## flex: grow shrink basis — the negotiation

```css
.item { flex: 1 1 0; }       /* grow:1 shrink:1 basis:0 — equal columns */
.sidebar { flex: 0 0 240px; } /* fixed 240px, never grows/shrinks */
.search { flex: 1; }          /* absorbs remaining space */
```

- **basis**: starting size (`0` = ignore content size → truly equal shares; `auto` = start from content)
- **grow**: share of *extra* space (proportional weights)
- **shrink**: how it gives up space under pressure

The overflow classic: flex items **refuse to shrink below content size** (`min-width: auto`) — a long unbreakable string blows the layout. Fix: `min-width: 0` on the item (plus `text-overflow: ellipsis` inside):

```css
.cell { flex: 1; min-width: 0; }
.cell span { overflow: hidden; text-overflow: ellipsis; white-space: nowrap; }
```

## Everyday recipes

```css
/* Center anything */ .center { display: flex; justify-content: center; align-items: center; }
/* Nav: logo left, actions right */ .nav { display: flex; } .spacer { flex: 1; }
/* Sticky footer card */ .card { display: flex; flex-direction: column; } .card-body { flex: 1; }
/* Wrapping tag list */ .tags { display: flex; flex-wrap: wrap; gap: 8px; }
```

Flexbox vs Grid boundary (next lesson): flex = content-driven, one dimension at a time (toolbars, nav, centering, distributing a row); grid = layout-driven, two dimensions (page scaffolding, card grids, forms).

# CSS Grid

Rows AND columns from the container down — the layout tool for page scaffolding, dashboards, forms, and galleries.

## Core vocabulary

```css
.layout {
    display: grid;
    grid-template-columns: 240px 1fr;          /* sidebar + fluid main */
    grid-template-rows: 56px 1fr 40px;          /* header, content, footer */
    grid-template-areas:
        "sidebar header"
        "sidebar main"
        "sidebar footer";
    gap: 16px;
    min-height: 100dvh;
}
.sidebar { grid-area: sidebar; }
.header  { grid-area: header; }
```

`fr` = share of free space (grow, grid edition). `grid-template-areas` makes the layout **readable as ASCII art** — and responsive redefinition is just new art in a media query.

## The one-liner that replaced media queries for card grids

```css
.cards {
    display: grid;
    grid-template-columns: repeat(auto-fill, minmax(280px, 1fr));
    gap: 16px;
}
```

As many ≥280px columns as fit, stretched equally, reflowing at every width — responsive without a single breakpoint. (`auto-fill` keeps empty tracks; `auto-fit` collapses them — visible when there are few items.)

## Forms — the killer boring use case

```css
.form { display: grid; grid-template-columns: max-content 1fr; gap: 12px 16px; align-items: center; }
/* labels column auto-sizes to the longest label; inputs share the rest — no more width guessing */
.full-width { grid-column: 1 / -1; }    /* span all columns (textarea, buttons row) */
```

## Placement and alignment

`grid-column: 1 / 3` (lines, not cells — n columns = n+1 lines), `span 2`; `justify-*` = inline axis, `align-*` = block axis (consistent with flexbox); `place-items: center` = both. Implicit rows (`grid-auto-rows`) catch overflow items.

## Grid + flex together (the real answer to 'which?')

Grid for the **macro** structure (page, panels, card matrix); flex for the **micro** (inside a card: header row, button group, centering an icon). They nest naturally — a grid area's content is often a flex column. Subgrid (now baseline-supported) lets nested grids align to parent tracks — card internals aligning across cards.

# Responsive, Modernized

## Media queries: viewport-based, still the frame

```css
/* Mobile-first: base styles = smallest screen, enhance upward */
.layout { display: grid; grid-template-columns: 1fr; }
@media (min-width: 768px) { .layout { grid-template-columns: 240px 1fr; } }
```

Mobile-first (`min-width` stacking) keeps the simple case unconditional. Standard-ish breakpoints (640/768/1024/1280) matter less than **content-driven** ones: add a breakpoint where *your* layout breaks, not where an iPhone model exists.

## Container queries — the component-era upgrade

The old problem: a card in the main column is wide; the *same card* in the sidebar is narrow — media queries can't tell the difference (viewport is identical!). Container queries respond to the **parent's size**:

```css
.card-host { container-type: inline-size; }

.card { display: flex; flex-direction: column; }
@container (min-width: 400px) {
    .card { flex-direction: row; }             /* horizontal when ITS container allows */
}
```

Components become **self-responsive** — correct in any slot, which is exactly what a component library needs (your dumb components + this = drop-anywhere UI). Baseline-supported in all modern browsers.

## Fluid sizing — fewer breakpoints overall

```css
/* clamp(min, preferred, max): typography that scales smoothly */
h1 { font-size: clamp(1.5rem, 1rem + 2.5vw, 2.5rem); }
.container { width: min(100% - 2rem, 1200px); margin-inline: auto; }
```

`clamp()` + `min()`/`max()` + grid's `auto-fill/minmax` (grid lesson) eliminate whole categories of breakpoint fiddling — the layout *interpolates* instead of jumping.

## The units cheat sheet

- `rem` — type, spacing (respects user font-size settings — accessibility!)
- `dvh` — full-height sections (`100dvh` accounts for mobile browser chrome; `100vh` overflows on phones)
- `cqw/cqi` — container-relative (pairs with container queries)
- `px` — borders, shadows, fine details
- Tap targets ≥ 44×44px; test real devices for hover-vs-touch (`@media (hover: hover)` gates hover-only affordances)

# Testing the Frontend That Matters

## The pyramid, frontend edition

| Layer | Tool | Testing what |
|---|---|---|
| Pure logic (validators, mappers, pipes, stores) | plain Jasmine/Jest/Vitest — no TestBed | most of your bugs, cheapest tests |
| Components | TestBed + Harnesses | template ↔ class integration |
| Critical user flows | Playwright/Cypress E2E | login, checkout — few, valuable, slow |

Inverted pyramids (all E2E) = slow, flaky suites nobody trusts. Push logic *out* of components (smart/dumb lesson pays off here: dumb components + pure services are trivially testable).

## Component tests that don't lie

```typescript
it('shows orders and emits selection', async () => {
    await TestBed.configureTestingModule({
        imports: [OrderListComponent],
        providers: [{ provide: OrdersApi, useValue: fakeApi }],   // DI = fake at the boundary
    }).compileComponents();

    const fixture = TestBed.createComponent(OrderListComponent);
    fixture.componentRef.setInput('orders', [order1, order2]);    // signal inputs
    await fixture.whenStable();

    const rows = fixture.nativeElement.querySelectorAll('[data-testid="order-row"]');
    expect(rows.length).toBe(2);                                   // assert the DOM, not internals
});
```

Principles: test through the **template** (what users see), not private methods/fields; select via `data-testid` (refactor-proof) not CSS classes; fake at DI boundaries (your DIP lesson's payoff), not deep internals. `provideHttpClientTesting` + `HttpTestingController` for API-layer tests: expect requests, flush responses, verify no extras.

## Component harnesses — testing via the user's API

Material/CDK ship **harnesses**: page-object-style APIs that survive internal DOM changes:

```typescript
const select = await loader.getHarness(MatSelectHarness);
await select.open(); await select.clickOptions({ text: 'Shipped' });
```

Write harnesses for your own complex components — E2E and unit tests share them.

## Async & time

`fakeAsync` + `tick(300)` makes debounce/timers deterministic (no real waiting, no flakes); `fixture.whenStable()` for promises; for observables prefer testing the **pipeline as a pure function** (marble tests where warranted) over spinning up components.

## What NOT to test

Angular itself (bindings render inputs — framework's job), implementation details (method call counts on self), snapshots-of-everything (change-detector noise, rubber-stamp updates). Coverage on logic-bearing code beats coverage theater on templates.
